{
  "terms": [
    {
      "term": "Ammeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "A dedicated instrument used to measure the flow of electric current in a circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think 'Amps' equals 'Ammeter'.",
      "misconception": "Beginners often use the generic term 'multimeter' when the specific instrument required for current is an ammeter."
    },
    {
      "term": "Voltmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical potential difference (voltage) between two points.",
      "anchor": "Think 'Volts' equals 'Voltmeter'.",
      "misconception": "Confusing the instrument name with the unit; you use a Voltmeter to measure Voltage."
    },
    {
      "term": "Ohmmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the electrical resistance of a component or circuit.",
      "anchor": "Think 'Ohms' equals 'Ohmmeter'.",
      "misconception": "Believing resistance can be measured while the circuit is powered up; an ohmmeter is typically used on dead circuits."
    },
    {
      "term": "Wattmeter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument used to measure the rate of electrical power being used at a single moment.",
      "anchor": "Think 'Watts' equals 'Wattmeter'.",
      "misconception": "Believing a wattmeter measures total energy used over an hour; it only measures the 'instant' power."
    },
    {
      "term": "Energy Meter",
      "simpleDefinition": "An instrument (often called a kWh meter) that measures the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time.",
      "anchor": "The 'electric meter' found in a domestic service cupboard that records usage for billing.",
      "misconception": "Confusing Energy with Power; Energy is the total amount used over time, not the speed it is being used at."
    }
  ],
  "anchorPhrases": [
    "Ammeters measure current in Amps.",
    "Voltmeters measure potential difference in Volts.",
    "Ohmmeters measure resistance in Ohms.",
    "Wattmeters measure instantaneous power in Watts.",
    "Energy meters measure total consumption in Kilowatt-hours (kWh)."
  ],
  "misconceptionTargets": [
    "Using 'multimeter' as a generic answer for every measurement task.",
    "Confusing the rate of power (Watts) with the total energy consumed (kWh).",
    "Mixing up the instrument name with the unit of measurement."
  ]
}

{
  "teachChecks": [
    {
      "title": "Measuring Fundamental Quantities",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure current, voltage, and resistance.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "To work safely and accurately as an electrician, you must select the correct tool for the specific electrical quantity you are testing. While modern multimeters can perform many tasks, you must identify the dedicated instrument for each measurement to maintain technical precision. To measure the flow of electric current in a circuit, you use an Ammeter. This measures the quantity in Amps.",
        "When you need to check the electrical potential difference, or 'pressure,' between two points, you use a Voltmeter to measure Volts. Finally, to find the electrical resistance of a component—how much it opposes the flow of current—you use an Ohmmeter to measure Ohms. Note that an ohmmeter is typically used on 'dead' circuits to prevent damage to the meter and ensure an accurate reading.",
        "Using the correct name for the instrument is vital; calling every device a 'multimeter' is a common mistake. In your technical training, always match the meter name to the unit: Amps use an Ammeter, Volts use a Voltmeter, and Ohms use an Ohmmeter."
      ],
      "hint": "Think about the unit of measurement for each quantity; the instrument name usually ends in '-meter'."
    },
    {
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "objective": "Identify the specific instruments used to measure electrical power and energy consumption.",
      "retrievalTextLines": [
        "Understanding the difference between power and energy is essential for billing and load calculations. Power is the instantaneous rate at which electricity is being used. To measure this 'real-time' power in Watts, we use a Wattmeter. It tells you exactly how much load is being drawn at that specific second, which is critical for ensuring circuits are not overloaded.",
        "On the other hand, electrical energy is the total amount of power consumed over a duration of time. This is measured in Kilowatt-hours (kWh) using an Energy Meter, often referred to as a kWh meter. You will see these installed at the intake position of every domestic property to record usage for billing purposes.",
        "A common misconception is thinking a Wattmeter measures total consumption; it does not. It only shows the rate of use at one moment. If you want to know the total 'work done' over a period, you must look at the Energy Meter. Keeping these two distinct ensures you can correctly assess both the immediate demand on a circuit and the long-term consumption of an installation."
      ],
      "hint": "One measures how fast you are using electricity right now (Watts), while the other measures the total amount used over time (kWh)."
    }
  ]
}

